  "prompt": "What were the causes of Bengal partition in 1905?",
  "response": "The partition of Bengal in 1905 was a significant event during the British colonial rule in India. Here are the key causes:\n\n1. Administrative Reasons\n- British claimed the Bengal Presidency was too large and difficult to administer\n- Wanted to divide the province for more efficient governance\n- Planned to create separate administrative units\n\n2. Political Motivations\n- Aimed to weaken Bengali political unity and nationalist movement\n- Sought to create divisions between Hindu and Muslim communities\n- Implemented \"divide and rule\" strategy\n\n3. Lord Curzon's Policy\n- Lord Curzon, then Viceroy of India, was the primary architect of the partition\n- Believed dividing Bengal would reduce growing nationalist sentiments\n- Wanted to control and suppress emerging nationalist movements\n\n4. Demographic Considerations\n- Created a Muslim-majority province in East Bengal\n- Attempted to create a separate political identity for Muslims\n- Hoped to create a wedge between Hindu and Muslim communities\n\n5. Strategic Implications\n- Wanted to reduce the influence of Bengali intellectuals and nationalists\n- Believed partition would weaken the emerging Indian independence movement\n\nThe partition sparked significant protests and became a turning point in India's nationalist struggle, eventually leading to its reversal in 1911.",
